  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2455226454" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2455226454" />
    <a title="Murtaza " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13716226-murtaza"><img alt="Murtaza " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531516448p2/13716226.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2455226454?book_show_action=true">Jul 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Murtaza " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Murtaza " href="/user/show/13716226-murtaza">Murtaza </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2455226454" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16445844522811987225">Camus thesis in this book is exemplified in its famous statement that, &quot;there is but one truly serious philosophical problem and that is suicide.&quot; Like much modern existentialist philosophy, the guiding principle amounts to an assertion that the world is a desert, and then proceeds to question whether or not you can (or should) survive it. Is it even worth surviving, or trying to survive for the brief moment that we exist anyways? Why not, as many do today despite unprecedented material wealth, </span>
  <span id="freeText16445844522811987225" style="display:none">Camus thesis in this book is exemplified in its famous statement that, "there is but one truly serious philosophical problem and that is suicide." Like much modern existentialist philosophy, the guiding principle amounts to an assertion that the world is a desert, and then proceeds to question whether or not you can (or should) survive it. Is it even worth surviving, or trying to survive for the brief moment that we exist anyways? Why not, as many do today despite unprecedented material wealth, just end life right now if existence itself is a meaningless void, barren of the metaphysical gardens and springs that certain charlatans have baselessly promised?<br /><br />This book did not resonate with me personally, but only because I don't share its basic premises about reality. Having said that, I think that its impossible for a fair reader not to sympathize with Camus. One even has to applaud him for honestly trying to engage with the undeniable absurdity of a life lived in the face of a silently indifferent universe. In his book, "Islam Between East and West," Alija Ali Izetbegovic, commented sympathetically on the fundamentally religious nature of both nihilist and absurdist philosophy, of which The Myth of Sisyphus is a signal example:<br /><br /><i>Nihilism and the philosophy of the absurd are the fruits of the most civilized and richest parts of the world. That philosophy speaks of “the perspectiveless world,” of “the psychically split and <br />disintegrated individual, of the world of deaf mute silence.” It is by no means a poisonous philosophy, as it is called by some people. In fact, it is very deep and instructive. It is an expression of man’s resistance, of his nonconsent to the world that is growing in a manner opposite to the very image of his own. It is man’s revolt against the one-dimensional world of civilization. For the same reasons, some people found modem nihilism a kind of religion and, as we will see, such a concept is not groundless. <br /><br />They both represent a negation of materialism and embrace this world with the same idea. The primeval anxiousness, the views beyond the grave, the desparate searching for a way out of the world in which man is a stranger — these ideas are common to both of them. The difference lies in the fact that nihilism does not find the way out, while religion claims to have found it.</i><br /><br />If human beings, after all, are merely products of the earth, as "natural" as trees and ants, what need for any cripplingly anxious philosophy to grapple with that base fact? Camus seems to argue that we should embrace existence the same way a tree embraces it, to grow for the sake of growing. We should exist passionately and in a spirit of revolt against the absurdity of existence itself. The mere act of exertion, like Sisyphus pushing his giant boulder, is a grounds for ecstasy and contentment when we sacrifice hope for anything better - hope being the root of all despair.<br /><br />This is a tough desert to live in and I'm not sure that everyone can. Nonetheless I can see how it might provide strength and spiritual sustenance for some people. It may also incentivize an activist view of life that is conducive to material improvement. All in all this is a thoughtful and humane book, though deceptively dense for its short length.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16445844522811987225" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

