  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3801697598" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3801697598" />
    <a title="Udit Nair" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3898791-udit-nair"><img alt="Udit Nair" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586003092p2/3898791.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3801697598?book_show_action=true">May 17, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Udit Nair" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Udit Nair" href="/user/show/3898791-udit-nair">Udit Nair</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141023991" href="/book/show/612957.The_Myth_of_Sisyphus">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3898791-udit-nair?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3801697598" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12296567841977588927">I am so glad that I didnt leave the book at the start after reading few pages. To be honest it took some time for me to absorb the depth of the thought underlined by the author. I knew I was going to like this work the moment these lines came - &quot; To be precise, god is maintained only through the negation of human reason.&quot; <br/><br/>A cursory read might tell you that it&apos;s an absurd book with absurd conclusions. But the more you analyze and let the author explain you the idea it all makes sense. The biggest</span>
  <span id="freeText12296567841977588927" style="display:none">I am so glad that I didnt leave the book at the start after reading few pages. To be honest it took some time for me to absorb the depth of the thought underlined by the author. I knew I was going to like this work the moment these lines came - " To be precise, god is maintained only through the negation of human reason." <br /><br />A cursory read might tell you that it's an absurd book with absurd conclusions. But the more you analyze and let the author explain you the idea it all makes sense. The biggest takeaway from the book is this - " It was precisely a question of finding out whether or not life had to have a meaning to be lived. It now becomes clear on the contrary that it will be lived all the better if it has no meaning." <br /><br />We humans are the master of our own days. When we look at a particular situation then we contemplate the series of unrelated actions which becomes our fate, created by us and soon sealed by death. Thus convinced of the wholly human origin of all that is human, blind man eager to see who knows that the night has no end, he is still on the go.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12296567841977588927" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


